default2.4. Re-designating an increased number of one-way smaller urban/city centre routes as able to be used as 
defaulttwo-way for cyclistsdefault. It is my observation in Brighton and Hove that cyclists, like water, will always prefer the shortest and quickest route, and wil
defaultl often be prepared to break the law on one-way streets to achieve this, thus compromising other road users’ and their own safety. A similar increase in the number of routes where all traffic except cyclists may turn right, left or go straight ahead would 
defaultbe helpful 
defaultfor the same reason.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default 
defaultBrighton &amp; Hove has introduced an extensive programme of 
default20mph zonesdefault, including many around schools
default. While not necessarily popular with 
defaultdrivers, it has been widely welcomed by cyclists and other road users as supporting
default road safety in general, not simply for cyclists. 
defaultIt should be noted that these zones are, in the main, not supported/’enforced’ by road humps, which could impede the comfortable passage of cyclists, buses and emergency vehicles.
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default 
defaultRoad repair and defaultmaintenancedefault generally should be carried out in a manner which does not leave a 
default“gutter gap”default where asphalt ceases before the kerb or verge: this creates a hazard for cyclists (and moped/motorbike users) when and if they are pushed towards the side of the ro
defaultad by traffic, or out of nervousness. Such improved road surfacing would also benefit pedestrians.
default&#xa0;
default2.7
default 
defaultPolice and traffic wardensdefault must be encouraged to clamp down on parking across cycle lanes, and the few cases where parking across cycle lanes is permitt
defaulted should be abolished. 
