default3. Helmetsdefault and cycle equipmentdefault&#xa0;
default3.1
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultI
default am NOT a supporter of compulsory bike helmet wearing, and in fact believe that legislating to make adult cycl
defaultists do so is counter-productive, as it militates against the ease and simplicity 
defaultof just getting on a bike and riding away
default. D
defaultata about the benefit
defaults
default or otherwise to individual cyclists’ safety from wearing helmets is polarised – at least for adults.  There is evidence showing that drivers see helmet-wearing cyclists as less vulnerable, and 
defaultthey 
defaultthus drive less carefully: there is also evidence indicat
defaulting that cyclists themselves cycle less carefully if they are wearing a helmet, for similar reasons. 
defaultFurther information, however, indicates that 
defaulthelmet wearing for childrendefault 
defaultis
default 
defaultbeneficial due to the different way in which children tend to fall from their b
defaultikes, compared to adults, 
defaultie
default children tend to sustain more head injuries when they fall from a bike than adults, although of course collisions with motorised transport are identically dangerous for all age groups.
default Improving road maintenance (see [2] above)
default would help reduce the need anyway!
